Preparatory meetings between the US and North Korea in Singapore and on the inter-Korean border will help both sides exchange views on key issues, especially denuclearization, in an effort to promote the Singapore summit, Chinese analysts said on Tuesday.US President Donald Trump said on Tuesday that a top-level official of North Korea is heading to New York for discussions about a possible meeting between US-North Korean leaders, according to the Xinhua News Agency.Kim Chang-son, a senior official of North Korea's State Affairs Commission, arrived in Singapore Monday night. A team of US government officials including White House Deputy Chief of Staff for Operations Joe Hagin, left US Yokota air base in Japan for Singapore on Monday, Japanese public broadcaster NHK reported on Tuesday."Sending Kim Chang-son, a top aide to North Korean leader Kim Jong-un, to Singapore for preparatory meetings shows that North Korea attaches great importance to the scheduled summit with Trump," Lü Chao, a research fellow at the Liaoning Academy of Social Sciences told the Global Times. "And the two sides will discuss security measures and other protocols for the summit," he said.The US and North Korea are working along two lines to ensure the historic summit, Lü said, as the two countries also held meetings on the inter-Korean border.The US delegation, led by Ambassador Sung Kim, and the North Korean delegation, led by Vice Foreign Minister Choe Son-hui, met on the border on Sunday and are expected to meet again as early as Tuesday and no later than Wednesday, the Yonhap News Agency reported on Tuesday."Ambassador Sung Kim is one of the US' most important experts on Korean Peninsula issues and Choe Son-hui always deals with US affairs in North Korea," Lü said. "Their meetings will focus more on detailed topics to be mentioned in the Singapore summit, including the denuclearization differences."Trump and Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe plan to meet in advance of the Singapore summit. The two leaders spoke over the phone on Monday, agreeing it was "imperative" to completely dismantle North Korea's nuclear weapons and ballistic missile program, the White House said."As a member of the former Six-Party Talks, Japan has always worried about being marginalized on the Korean Peninsula issue," Lü said. "It wants to maintain close consultations with the US over the Singapore summit."China has played a constructive role in promoting the summit, he said. Backgrounder: the AIIB explainedImpact of anti-corruption campaignBig changes in China's top military brass Social credit system must bankrupt discredited people: former official B&R needs broader supportCCTV camera maker brands latest US bill as 'groundless' Flying taxis face many hurdles before public use in major citiesCA governor's race heats upTour of California How To Say Love To A Chinese Girl

